<DOC><DOCNO>  ZF207-298-091  </DOCNO><DOCID>07 298 091.andO;</DOCID><JOURNAL>Computer Design  Jan 1 1989 v28 n1 p22(2).andM;</JOURNAL><TITLE>Single-board computer merges VME and STE buses. (includes relatedarticle on the STE bus community)</TITLE><AUTHOR>Lieberman, David.andM;</AUTHOR><TEXT><ABSTRACT>Introduction of the FSC020 VMEbus CPU board (Arcom ControlSystems) allows OEMs to purchase a board that provides the basichardware integration of the STE bus and the 32-bit VMEbus, withoutthe price of a backplane slot.andP;  Arcom has made the integration onthe daughter board of a VMEbus single-board computer.andP;  The boardgives VME designers the availability of a wealth of low-costindustrial STE I-O boards from a lot of vendors.andP;  The STE designerlikes the mixed-bus design because it represents an upgradestrategy.andP;  Arcom is pushing the board as a simpler, cheaperinterface.andP;  A typical 6U VMEbus board has twice the functionalityof a 3U STE bus board, but it costs four times as much.andP;  Also, thesimplicity of the interface saves money over 16- and 32-bitsystems in both design time and production cost.andM;</ABSTRACT></TEXT><DESCRIPT>Company:   Arcom Control Systems Ltd (products).andO;Product:   Arcom Control Systems VSC020 (Circuit board) (design andconstruction).andO;Topic:     VMEbusInterfaceCircuit DesignCPU.andO;Feature:   illustrationphotograph.andM;</DESCRIPT></DOC>